  "finger_focus": "Email rhythm + tone",
  "tips": [
    {
      "type": "lead",
      "text": "Most working days you will write more emails than you read. Treat each one like copy: clear, brief, said once."
    },
    {
      "type": "drop",
      "text": "An email has three beats - greeting, body, signoff. Type all three in one breath and the tone stays even."
    },
    {
      "type": "exercise",
      "target": "Hi Sarah, thank you for the update on the Q3 roadmap. I reviewed the projections and they look solid. One question: can",
      "finger": "purple",
      "hint": "Email rhythm + tone"
    },
    {
      "type": "p",
      "text": "The comma after Hi Sarah and after Best should land without a thought. Small marks, but readers notice when they go missing."
    },
    {
      "type": "exercise",
      "target": "we shift the marketing launch to mid-August? That would give the engineering team an extra week. Looking forward to your reply. Best, Alex.",
      "finger": "purple",
      "hint": "Email rhythm + tone"
    }
  ],
  "character_tips": {
    "anna": "Email is the plain bread of working life. Get the rhythm right and the whole day moves easier. - Eleanor Hayes, editor",
    "maxim": "Write a clean note quickly and you buy yourself hours over a week. The trick is to type the whole thing, not stop to admire it. - Eleanor Hayes, editor",
    "knopych": "Don't attack the inbox. Answer it - one clear note at a time, then move on. - Eleanor Hayes, editor",
    "klavochka": "Polite, clear, and short. A good email reads like a good letter: nothing wasted. - Eleanor Hayes, editor"
  },
